The subfamily Rhyssalinae is phylogenetically one of the most basal taxonomic group within the family Braconidae and is currently represented by five extant tribes, Achaiabraconini
, Acrisidini Hellén, 1957 , Histeromerini Fahringer, 1930 , Laibaleini
, and Rhyssalini Foerster, 1963 (
;
) and one recently described fossil tribe
Electroncophanini Belokobylskij & Zaldívar-Riverón, 2023
(
).

Baltic amber is the most famous and richest depositary of fossil insects of the late Eocene age (33.9±0.1– 37.2±0.1 Mya) (

). Most of the amber material which has been investigated is deposited along the eastern part of the south shore of the Baltic Sea (especially in the 
Kaliningrad Province
of 
Russia
).

The studied amber originated from the 
Primorskiy
quarry, near Yantarnyi in the 
Kaliningrad Province
(
Russia
), the age of which is estimated as Priabonian (Late Eocene) (

; 

).

The material used for this study is deposited in the collection of the 
Kaliningrad
Amber Museum (KAM; 
Russia
).

